# Legal Contract Lookup — RAG System

## Project goal
A chat interface for querying legal contracts (NDAs, employment agreements,
non-compete, royalty agreements) with cited clause-level answers.
Users can also upload their own contracts and ask questions against them.

## Stack
- Python 3.11
- LangChain for orchestration
- ChromaDB for vector storage
- BM25 (rank_bm25) for keyword retrieval
- Cohere reranker API for reranking (rerank-english-v3.0)
- Claude API for answer generation
- RAGAS for evaluation
- Streamlit for UI

## Key design decisions
- Page-then-chunk strategy: pdf_parser produces per-page Documents (pdfplumber);
  chunker splits each page with `RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter` at 300 tokens
  with 50 overlap (cl100k_base via tiktoken). Layout-aware chunking via
  Unstructured `strategy="fast"` was tried and abandoned — title detection was
  unreliable across the corpus (median chunk ~24 tokens, frequent body-as-title
  false positives). If page-level citations turn out too coarse in eval, the
  fallback is Docling (heavier install, real layout model) — not Unstructured tuning.
- `clause_number` metadata is best-effort: regex-detected from each chunk's
  leading text (`Section X`, `Article Y`, `Clause Z.W`, or leading "N.M" headings).
  May be `None` — citations must work without it.
- Every answer must cite `source + page`; include `clause_number` when present.
- Hybrid retrieval: BM25 (exact clause/party name matches) + vector
  (semantic meaning) → RRF → Cohere rerank → LLM. Always applied within a
  SINGLE collection.
- Two ChromaDB collections: `base_contracts` (preloaded demo corpus) and
  `session_<session_id>` (per-user uploads, cleared on session end).
- Mode-switch retrieval (NOT merge): each query targets exactly one
  collection. If the user has uploaded docs in this session → query the
  session collection only; otherwise → query base only. Base is demo/example
  content (BIRAC royalty template, sample employment agreement, etc.) and
  has no semantic relationship to a user's real contract — merging would
  pollute relevance with template language and produce mixed-source
  citations. The mode is reflected in the result dict (`mode: "base"|"session"`)
  so the UI can label it explicitly.
- Evaluation driven by real questions from a legal practitioner

## Document upload feature
- Users upload PDFs via Streamlit file uploader
- Indexed into session-scoped ChromaDB collection on upload
- Max 10MB per file, max 5 files per session
- Session docs cleared on session end (no persistence in v1)

## Conventions
- All retrievers return List[Document] with metadata:
  {source, clause_number, page, contract_type, collection}
  `clause_number` may be `None`/`""` (best-effort field). Other keys required.
- Retrievers may add stage-specific score annotations on top of this schema:
  `bm25_score` (BM25), `similarity_score` (vector), `rrf_score` (RRF fusion),
  `rerank_score` (Cohere reranker). These are stripped before generation —
  the LLM only sees the canonical metadata above.
- Never hallucinate clause content — if not found, say explicitly
- Chunks: target 300 tokens (within 200-400 band), 50 token overlap
- collection field in metadata = "base" or "session"

## Build order
[x] 1. Ingestion pipeline (pdf_parser ✓, chunker ✓, indexer ✓)
[x] 2. BM25 retrieval
[x] 3. Vector retrieval (base collection)
[x] 4. RRF fusion
[x] 5. Reranker (Cohere rerank-english-v3.0; graceful fallback to input order)
[x] 6. LLM generation with citations (Claude sonnet-4; [N] citation parsing; graceful fallback)
[x] 7. Session store (per-session Chroma collection + in-memory BM25 dict; thread-safe; idempotent)
[x] 8. Streamlit UI with file uploader (app.py: chat + sidebar + citations + sources-used + mode badge)
[x] 9. RAGAS eval pipeline (eval/run_eval.py: 15-question golden set across 5 categories;
       Faithfulness/AnswerRelevancy/LLMContextPrecisionWithReference/LLMContextRecall/AnswerCorrectness;
       Claude as judge via LangchainLLMWrapper; BGE-small for embedding-based metrics;
       per-question CSV + per-category summary; mode-locked to base corpus)